@endnode

@node "I." "FEATURES"
- can easily be configured via ascii-files

- pictures for telescope mode are automatically recognized

- functions can be chosen by @{"DROPDOWN MENUS" link "Screen" 0}, @{"SHORTCUTS" link "V.I." 0} or @{"GADGETS" link "Screen" 0}

- slideshow-mode

- double-buffered-display ! ( see @{"KNOWN BUGS" link "VII." 0} )

- friendly with multitasking : while nothing happens, task is set to
  'waiting'

- saves its @{"default settings" link "VI." 0} at the end of a session

- can always be switched to @{"other languages" link "V.II." 0}

- now shows a lot more of stars and other objects

- you can choose your observation point on a worldmap and jump to preset
  locations via gadgets
@endnode

@node "II." "Some remarks"
 This program was originally written for the C64 by H. Hinkelmann and first
published in the C64 Magazin 5/85 (Markt & Technik).

I ported it to the Amiga, adding a lot of stars and new features, making  use of
intuition, thus re-coding the whole thing. I reorganized the whole stucture of
the program and its routines speeding them up and that's why I sign as author.

Meanwhile the program is quite stable and as I have put a lot of time into it I
give you the newest version as FRIENDWARE, which means I hope you will write me
a letter, if you  enjoy this program.

If you @{"register" link "X." 0} you will be informed when a new version is available.

Anyway, donations (money, science fiction of all kind, CD's, cars, houses...)
are wellcome and will entitle you to a free update (if there is one) and the
sourcecode.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
ATTENTION!! I MAY NOT BE HELD RESPONSIBLE FOR ANY DAMAGE THIS PROGRAM MIGHT DO
TO YOUR HARDWARE, SOFTWARE, TUPPERWARE OR BRAIN, SO BE CAREFUL!
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Orginally written on a 1Meg A2000 under Kick 1.3 the program turned out to run
well with 1Meg chipmemory and 6Meg fastram under Kick 3.1 and the A2630, though
some "friends" of GFA-basic would not expect it.

(-> @{"KNOWN BUGS" link "VII." 0})


 
                                 ATTENTION
                                 =========

I encourage you to pass this package to anyone you want under the condition that
the files remain unchanged and complete! (see @{"copyright" link "VIII." 0})
                      ======================
@endnode

@node "III." "Contents"

 - three archivs
        
        TELE1.LHA       graphics for telescope-mode and diashow

 Since version 3.0 of PLANETARIUM additional graphics are distributed separetely 
 as Plan_pix.lha
                        

        PLAN.LHA        containing

                 - Planetarium.loader       loading module
                 - Planetarium.exe          main program
                 - Planetarium.loader.info  program icon
                 - Planetarium.c            compiled version (without double-
                                            buffering for AGA and slow Amigas)
                 - Planetarium.c.info       program icon
                 - Planetarium.guide.info   texticon
                 - Planetarium.guide        german/english guide
                 - Planetarium.pic          starting-sreen
                 - plan.prefs               preferences file; your own preferences
                                            will be stored to ENV: and ENVARC:
                                            or S: depending on your system
                 - map.pic                  Worldmap
                 - about.eng                ASCII-file for Info (english)
                 - about.fra                ASCII-file for Info (french)
                 - about.ger                ASCII-file for Info (german)
                 - const.eng                ASCII-file for constellations
                 - const.fra                ASCII-file for constellations
                 - const.ger                ASCII-file for constellations
                 - defstrings.eng           ASCII-file with all needed strings
                 - defstrings.fra           s.a. french version
                 - defstrings.fer           s.a. german version
                 - @{"preset.data" link "V.III." 0}              ASCII-file for presets
                 - planet.data              ASCII-file for planets
                 - starneu.data             ASCII-file for stars
                 - gfabasro                 Run-only-Interpreter

and the files

                 - MuchMore                     textviewer
                 - BITTE_LESEN.info             texticon
                 - BITTE_LESEN                  installationhelp german
                 - READ_ME_FIRST.info           texticon
                 - READ_ME_FIRST                Installationhelp english
                 - Installer                    Commodores utility
                 - Install-Planetarium          simple installerscript
                 - Install-Planetarium.info     scripticon
                 - AmigaGuide                   Commodore utility

               - libs                           library-drawer
                    - amigaguide.library

               - tools                          tools-drawer
                    - LhA                       (de-)archiving utility
                    - LhaPatterns               utilityprogram for lha
@endnode

@node "IV." "Overview"
 PLANETARIUM draws a chart of stars from horizon to horizon for any place on
earth and any reasonable time (it calculates the Julian Date).

 +------------------------------------------------------------------------+
 | It starts with the time (and date) it gets from your system, expecting |
 | you to live in the timezone of the first pre-set place. If you do not, |
 | you should correct this in @{"preset.data" link "V.III." 0} using any ASCII-editor.         |
 +------------------------------------------------------------------------+

You can change time and date selecting the appropriate item from the
pulldown-menu.

Most stars down to third magnitude are shown and some fainter are added where
the constellation requires them. Magnitude and apparent brightness correspond to
the colours (grayscale) used by the program, planets are marked red.

PLANETARIUM is ment to help the astronomical beginner:

First, it helps to locate stars, constellations and planets. Point at a star on
the chart and press the left mousebutton: A circle is drawn around it, its name
and that of its constellation are displayed while the other stars of the
constellation are blinking.

If you know the name of a star, planet or constellation and don't know where it
is, select 'Look for names' from the @{"DROPDOWN MENUS" link "Screen" 0} , enter the name or part  of
it and everything will be displayed as mentioned above.

Second, PLANETARIUM is able to simulate the movements of celestial objects. Just
select 'Planetarium' from the 'MODE'-menu or click its icon. Choosing an
twentyfour-hour interval will show you the motion of sun, moon and planets in
front of the fixed stars.
@endnode

